\f0\b\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 3. CLAUDE.md / AGENTS.md \'97 The Master Onboarding File\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 Purpose:
\f1\b0 \'a0This is the first file an AI agent reads at the start of every session. It serves as the agent's "onboarding guide" to your project \'97 the equivalent of a new hire's first-day briefing.\'a0
\f2 CLAUDE.md
\f1 \'a0is the Anthropic/Claude Code convention;\'a0
\f2 AGENTS.md
\f1 \'a0is the open standard equivalent used by Cursor, Codex, Windsurf, and others.\

\f0\b What it should cover (the WHAT / WHY / HOW framework):
\f1\b0 \
The file should tell the agent\'a0
\f0\b WHAT
\f1\b0 \'a0it's working with (the tech stack, project structure, monorepo layout),\'a0
\f0\b WHY
\f1\b0 \'a0the project exists and what each component does (the purpose and function of different parts), and\'a0
\f0\b HOW
\f1\b0 \'a0it should work on the project (build commands, test commands, verification steps, runtime choices like\'a0
\f2 bun
\f1 \'a0vs\'a0
\f2 node
\f1 ).\

\f0\b Critical best practices from research and production teams:
\f1\b0 \

\f0\b Less is more.
\f1\b0 \'a0Research shows frontier thinking LLMs can reliably follow roughly 150\'96200 instructions. Claude Code's own system prompt already consumes about 50 of those. The more instructions you cram in, the more uniformly the model ignores\'a0
\f4\i all
\f1\i0 \'a0of them \'97 not just the new ones. The HumanLayer team's production\'a0
\f2 CLAUDE.md
\f1 \'a0is under 60 lines. Community consensus puts the ideal length at under 300 lines, with shorter being better.\

\f0\b Keep it universally applicable.
\f1\b0 \'a0Since this file is injected into every single conversation, everything in it should be relevant to every task. Avoid putting database schema instructions here that will only matter for database work. Claude Code literally wraps this file with a system instruction saying "this context may or may not be relevant to your tasks. You should not respond to this context unless it is highly relevant" \'97 so irrelevant content actively gets filtered out.\

\f0\b Use progressive disclosure.
\f1\b0 \'a0Instead of stuffing all project knowledge into one file, keep task-specific instructions in separate markdown files and use the master file as a\'a0
\f4\i routing table
\f1\i0 \'a0that points to them:\
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\f5\fs26 \cf2 \cb9 Copy\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f6\b\fs28 \cf10 \cb3 \strokec10 # CLAUDE.md
\f2\b0 \cf5 \strokec5 \
\

\f6\b \cf10 \strokec10 ## Project Overview
\f2\b0 \cf5 \strokec5 \
Monorepo for the Acme platform. Web app + API + mobile.\
\

\f6\b \cf10 \strokec10 ## Architecture
\f2\b0 \cf5 \strokec5 \
See \cf8 \strokec8 `agent_docs/service_architecture.md`\cf5 \strokec5  for details.\
\

\f6\b \cf10 \strokec10 ## Building & Testing
\f2\b0 \cf5 \strokec5 \
See \cf8 \strokec8 `agent_docs/building_the_project.md`\cf5 \strokec5  for commands.\
\

\f6\b \cf10 \strokec10 ## Code Conventions
\f2\b0 \cf5 \strokec5 \
See \cf8 \strokec8 `agent_docs/code_conventions.md`\cf5 \strokec5  \'97 read before making PRs.\
\

\f6\b \cf10 \strokec10 ## Key Rules
\f2\b0 \cf5 \strokec5 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf11 \strokec11 -\cf5 \strokec5  Use bun, not npm\
\cf11 \strokec11 -\cf5 \strokec5  Never commit directly to main\
\cf11 \strokec11 -\cf5 \strokec5  Run \cf8 \strokec8 `bun test`\cf5 \strokec5  before suggesting any PR\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 \strokec2 Prefer pointers to copies.
\f1\b0 \'a0Don't paste code snippets into these docs \'97 they go stale fast. Use\'a0
\f2 file:line
\f1 \'a0references to point the agent to the authoritative source.\

\f0\b Don't use\'a0
\f6 /init
\f0 \'a0or auto-generate it.
\f1\b0 \'a0This is the highest-leverage file in your entire agent setup. A bad line here multiplies into bad plans, bad code, and bad outcomes across every session. Craft it by hand.\

\f0\b Don't use it as a linter.
\f1\b0 \'a0LLMs are expensive and slow compared to deterministic formatters. Use hooks that run Biome/ESLint/Prettier after the agent generates code, rather than asking the agent to enforce code style itself.\

