\f2  2026\cf15 \strokec15 -03-30\cf5 \strokec5 .md\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \strokec2 A critical experimental finding:\'a0
\f0\b raw logs beat curated summaries.
\f1\b0 \'a0In a controlled experiment with the same agent, same 20 questions, and 4 different memory configurations, the agent with messy raw daily logs scored 4.55/5, while the one with carefully written curated documentation scored only 2.65/5 \'97\'a0
\f4\i below
\f1\i0 \'a0the baseline of having no memory at all (3.30/5). Why? Curated summaries strip out uncertainty, making the agent overconfident. Raw logs preserve the debugging sessions, wrong turns, and "we tried X and it failed" moments that keep reasoning honest.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 11d. Context Compaction \'97 "Sleep, Not Death"\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 When context grows too long, the conversation compacts. The key reframe: think of this as\'a0
\f4\i sleep
\f1\i0 , not death. The agent "wakes up" and reconstructs itself from memory files. If your memory structure is good, compaction barely hurts. If it's bad, every compaction is brain damage. This is why having well-structured MEMORY.md and SOUL.md files is essential \'97 they're the agent's identity and knowledge that survive the "sleep" cycle.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 11e. When to Use Databases Instead\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 The Markdown approach is optimal for\'a0
\f0\b local agents
\f1\b0 \'a0where context is finite and structured. The database approach (vector DBs, LangGraph checkpointers, etc.) is optimal for\'a0
\f0\b enterprise agents
\f1\b0 \'a0with millions of user profiles and history logs that can't fit in a single file. The crossover point tends to be around 5MB of memory files / 10,000+ documents \'97 beyond that, you need semantic search infrastructure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb4 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

