\f0\b\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 14. Lessons from Manus \'97 Context Engineering at Scale\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 Manus (the $2B agent startup) developed several context engineering principles that apply broadly:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 Design around the KV-cache.
\f1\b0 \'a0Keep your prompt prefix stable (don't include timestamps at the start), make context append-only, and ensure deterministic JSON serialization. The cost difference between cached and uncached tokens is 10x with Claude.\

\f0\b Mask, don't remove.
\f1\b0 \'a0When the agent doesn't need certain tools, don't remove them from the context (which breaks the cache). Instead, use logit masking to prevent the agent from selecting them.\

\f0\b Use the file system as context.
\f1\b0 \'a0When the context window isn't enough, write to and read from files on demand. The file system is unlimited, persistent, and directly operable by the agent.\

\f0\b Manipulate attention through recitation.
\f1\b0 \'a0By constantly rewriting a todo.md file, the agent pushes its global plan into its most recent attention span, preventing goal drift in 50+ step tasks.\

\f0\b Keep the wrong stuff in.
\f1\b0 \'a0Don't erase failed actions from context. When the model sees a failed action and the resulting error, it implicitly updates its beliefs and avoids repeating the mistake. Error recovery is one of the clearest indicators of true agentic behavior.\

\f0\b Don't get few-shotted.
\f1\b0 \'a0If context is full of similar action-observation pairs, the model mimics the pattern even when it's no longer optimal. Introduce structured variation in serialization and phrasing to break monotony.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
